Quality control of Sequencing Reads

Potential QC tools

  • Seqkit
  • Fastqc
  • MultiQC
  • BBDuk script
  • Trimmomatic
  • Kneaddata

Required resources

  • Adapter fasta files
  • PhiX fasta file

QC environment.yml

name: readqc
channels:
    - bioconda
    - biobakery
dependencies:
    - seqkit =2.3.1
    - fastqc =0.12.1
    - multiqc =1.14
    - bbmap =39.01
    - trimmomatic =0.39
    - knead-data =0.12.0
conda activate base
mamba install -c bioconda -c conda-forge -n readqc -file environment.yml

Snakemake workflow rules


Tentative snakemake workflow



Getting the read statistics

Quick glimpse

Assuming that the seqkit tool is installed, we can use it to get the simple statistics of the reads.

  • If the files are uncompressed we may want to save space by compressing them.
  • Let’s navigate to the folder containing the fastq files and compress them using gzip function.
gzip *.fastq

From this point foward we will assume that all the fastq files are in fastq.gz format. We will use the seqkit tool to compute read statistics which contain useful information for preparing sample mapping files.

#!/bin/bash

echo PROGRESS: Getting stats of the raw reads.

INPUTDIR="resources/reads"
SEQKIT="results/qc/seqkit1"
mkdir -p "${SEQKIT}"
seqkit stat "${INPUTDIR}"/*.fastq.gz >"${SEQKIT}"/seqkit_stats.txt


Read Quality Control tools

Quick glimpse

  • Assuming that the most QC tools are installed, it is time to use them to do the following:
    • Check the quality of the reads.
    • Create summary report of quality metrics.
    • Trim poor read at a user-specified cutoff.
    • Remove contaminants.

Screenshot of interactive snakemake report

The interactive snakemake HTML report can be viewed by opening the report.html using any compatible browser. You will be able to explore the workflow and the associated statistics. You can close the left bar to get a more expansive display view.
